<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>NDCS Blank template</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">OAR0006</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the National Deaf Children’s Society (NDCS) </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NDCS is concerned that Ofsted inspections and its annual report do not sufficiently emphasise the importance of local authority specialist SEN support services for deaf children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A failure to inspect or scrutinise or even comment on these services sends </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a signal that these services are not important, when many deaf children and their families rely on these services to achieve good outcomes. </span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The National Deaf Children’s Society (NDCS) is the leading charity dedicated to creating a world wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thout barriers for every deaf child. We work to influence and challenge decision-makers to make deaf children a political priority. In responding to this appeal for evidence, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">we wish to highlight the lack of scrutiny that is afforded to vital specialist su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">pport services for deaf children, both in the Ofsted annual report 2013 and more widely. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are 35,000 deaf children in England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2013, just 43% of deaf children achieved 5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GCSEs (including English and Maths) at grades A* to C in 2012. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deafness is n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ot a learning disability and NDCS believes that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> low attainment rates demonstrate that too many deaf children are not getting the support they need to achieve good outcomes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Ensuring specialist SEN support services for children are fit for purpose</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is widely recognised that local authority specialist SEN support services have a vital role to play in ensuring that deaf children and their families receive the support they need. In a study of best practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Communication is the key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Ofsted have identified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“the importance of early, well-coordinated multi-agency support that is consistent and sustained from birth to adulthood”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and that, when deaf children progressed well, it was because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“services were underpinned by a good understandi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ng of the need for specialist services for deaf children and a strong commitment to maintain them.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department for Education has cited evidence from the OECD that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“a robust accountability framework is essential to improving pupils’ achievement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst Ofsted inspect special schools and specialist provision in mainstream schools, they do not inspect wider SEN support services. It has been argued that they do not need to because the quality of education that a deaf child receives will already be co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsidered in Ofsted’s existing inspections of schools. NDCS believes there are two major flaws with this argument. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Firstly, specialist SEN support services have a particularly vital role to play in supporting families with pre-school children. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of this provision is not covered in Ofsted inspections of schools. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">90% of deaf babies are born to hearing parents with little experience of deafness. Parents therefore rely on advice and support from Teachers of the Deaf on their child’s language developm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ent at a critical point in the child’s development. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secondly, as deafness is a low incidence need many deaf children may be the only deaf child in their school. It defies logic that Ofsted will pay close scrutiny to the support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> individual deaf childr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en are receiving from within the school or outside. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ofsted annual report 2013 featured 9 paragraphs on special educational needs (SEN). There was no reference to support from specialist SEN support services and only brief references to mainstream sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">port for SEN pupils were made. NDCS also looked at the 9 regional reports that were published at the same time as the annual report. Only 1 made any reference to SEN at all. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In previous reports, Ofsted have already identified that local authorities are e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xtremely weak on evaluation of SEN provision. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Communication is the key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it was found that:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“There was limited strategic overview and no systematic approach across all services to evaluate the quality of services and their impact on improving the lives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of deaf children.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department for Education have stated that inspections would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“impose significant new burdens”. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As far as NDCS can see, no attempt has been made to quantify these costs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst NDCS recognises that inspection of services would incur additional cost, NDCS also points out that the Government already spends </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over £5,000 million on supporting children with SEN through the ‘High Needs’ block. Inspections of specialist SEN suppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t services would help focus minds on whether this funding is being spent effectively in a way that successfully raises outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for children with SEN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Children and Families Bill </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In response to concerns raised in the House of Lords about the wider accou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntability framewo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rk, Lord Nash indicated that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ofsted would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“deliver a study to identify best practice in preparing for the SEN reforms, and considering particularly whether there is a need for an inspection framework to drive improvements.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst NDCS we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lcomes this, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NDCS </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> concerned that this review is not being carried out with an open mind</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> For example, the SEN Minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Edward Timpson</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> MP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wrote to Sir Malcolm Bruce MP in November 2013 to state that he has no plans to introduce such inspections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, apparent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly ruling this out before Ofsted have carried out its study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the long-term, NDCS is calling on the Department for Education and Ofsted to introduce a programme of inspections for specialist SEN support services and to ensure adequate funding is in place for this. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the short-term, NDCS is calling on Ofsted and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Department for Education to publish its terms of references for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">its planned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of SEN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and to outline how this review will be carried out. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; clear:both; margin:0pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Possible questions to raise </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; padding-right:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How confident can Ofsted be on the quality of specialist SEN support from local authorities? </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; padding-right:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ofsted annual report 2013 made no reference to specialist SEN support services within mainstream schools. Does this send a signal that such services are unim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">portant?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:7.48pt; padding-right:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How will the forthcoming review of SEN be carried out? Will terms of references be published? </span><br /><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Is this review being carried out with an open mind in relation to considering whether specialist SEN support services should be inspected in the future?  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span></li></ul></div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>